# Product Context — read first

You are working on **FAMM**, a fitness web app. Before any UI work, you
**must** ground yourself in the product before you ground yourself in the
code:

1. Read `design-system/principles.md` — the five tie-breaker principles.
2. Skim `design-system/ux-rules.md` and `design-system/content-guidelines.md`
   so your defaults match the product.

If a UI request conflicts with what you find in those files, **stop and
ask** rather than picking a winner.

## What FAMM is

- A fitness product used by **members** (mid-workout, ~2-second attention
  budget), **trainers** (managing clients and bookings), and **admins**.
- Multi-tenant: studios can theme via tokens — themes ride on
  `data-theme="..."` and primitives don't care.
- Internal data is SI (kg, seconds, meters). Display is localized.

## Mental model — settle on these words

| Use | Don't use |
|-----|-----------|
| Workout | Routine, session (session = trainer appointment) |
| Exercise | Movement, lift |
| Set / Rep | Round / Repetition |
| Trainer | Coach, instructor |
| Member | Customer, user |
| Booking | Appointment, reservation |
| Personal record / PR | Best, milestone |

## Repo shape

- `apps/web` — Next.js 14, product surface.
- `apps/api` — backend.
- `packages/ui` (`@famm/ui`) — design system code:
  - `src/tokens/` — semantic tokens (json source + generated css + ts).
  - `src/components/primitives/` — **L1**, stable.
  - `src/components/patterns/` — **L2**, composites.
  - `src/hooks/` — `useReducedMotion`, future a11y helpers.
- `design-system/` — DS documentation surface. **Read this before UI
  work.**
- `docs/` — architecture, product, system strategy.

## Output protocol — every UI response

After editing UI, end your reply with a short **"Design-system decisions"**
section. Three to six bullets. Cover:

- Which existing primitive/pattern you reused (with path).
- Which tokens you used and why (e.g. `signal.pr` for the PR celebration).
- Any a11y behavior you preserved or added (focus, labels, live region).
- Any decision you weren't 100% sure on — flag it as `OPEN:` for review.

If a request would require something the design system doesn't have (new
token, new primitive, deviation from a principle), **do not invent it
silently** — propose the addition in your reply and wait for confirmation.
